					<head>Hagadah</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/n79084774" rend="visible">
						<summary>Hagadah for Passover according to the Spanish rite (the 'Hispano-Moresque Hagadah').</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he">Hebrew</textLang>
						<msItem rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/n79084774">
							<locus from="1r" to="93v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he">הגדה של פסח</title>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Hagadah shel Pesaḥ </title>
							<msItem rend="">
								<locus from="1v" to="6r"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Introduction</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="">
								<locus from="6r" to="46v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Hagadah</title>
								<note>
									<p>The commentary starts on folio <locus n="6v"/>.</p>
								</note>
							</msItem>
							<note>
								<p>After the Halel section are the two alphabetical pieces, on folio 32v and 33v respectively.</p>
								<p>On folio 36r begins the targumic paraphrase of Be-shalaḥ; the alphabetical piece Azil Mosheh begins on folio 42v; the targumic paraphrase of Ex. 19 opens on folio 49v; the beginning of the Ten Commandments on folio 53v.</p>
								<p>The Hafṭarot for the Passover are written in the upper and lower margins of folio 4v-33r, in a small semi-cursive script. The targum is added after each verse, except in 2Sam. 22. </p>
								<p>See further Mendel Metzger, ‘Two Fragments of a Spanish XIVth Century Haggadah,’ Gesta, 6 (1967), pp. 25-34;
Bezalel Narkiss, Hebrew Illuminated Manuscripts in the British Isles : a catalogue raisonne´. The Spanish and Portuguese Manuscripts, 2 vols (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1982), I, no. 9; II, figs 79-104; Therese and Mendel Metzger, Jewish Life in the Middle Ages: Illuminated Hebrew Manuscripts of the Thirteenth to the Sixteenth Centuries (New York: Alpine Fine Arts Collection, 1982), p. 304; Yael Zirlin, &apos;The Schocken Italian Haggadah of c. 1400 and Its Origins&apos;, Jewish Art, 12/13 (1986/87), 54-72 (pp. 63-72);
Joseph Gutmann, &apos;The Sacrifice of Isaac in Medieval Jewish Art&apos; Artibus et Historiae, 8 (1987), 67-89 (pp. 74, 85); Katrin Kogman-Appel, Jewish Book Art Between Islam and Christianity: the Decoration of Hebrew Bibles in Medieval Spain (Lieden: Brill, 2004), pp. 94-95; Ilana Tahan, Hebrew Manuscripts: The Power of Script and Image (London, British Library, 2007), pp. 90-93; Sacred: Books of the Three Faiths: Judaism, Christianity, Islam (London: British Library, 2007), p. 160 [exhibition catalogue]; Julie Harris, &apos;Love in the Land of Goshen&apos;, Gesta 52 no. 2 (2013), pp. 161-180. </p>
							</note>
							<decoNote type="illustration">Picture cycle of 63 full-page miniatures with coloured washes.<locus from="62v" to="93v"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="miniature">2 full-page miniatures at the beginning and at the end of the text of the Haggadah. <locus n="1r, 35v"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="illustration">5 textual illustrations. <locus n="9v, 20v, 21r, 22r, 22v"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="initial">Numerous decorated initial-word panels with gold letters. </decoNote>
							<decoNote type="border">Embellished vertical band with keywords of texts on two folios. <locus n="18v, 19r"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="paratext">Numerous rubrics.</decoNote>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of last quarter of the 13th century or 1st quarter of the 14th century, c. 1300.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment.</support>
								<extent>93 folios <dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>160</height>
										<width>120</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>90/95</height>
										<width>60/65</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>93 folios (+ an unfoliated leaf after folio 3, three modern paper flyleaves and a parchment flyleaf from before 1884 at the beginning, and a parchment flyleaf, an older paper flyleaf, and three modern paper flyleaves at the end).</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>13 quires: i4 (folios 1-3*), ii8 (folios 4-11), iii8 (folios 12-19), iv6 (folios 20-25), v8 (folios 26-33), vi8 (folios 34-41), vii8 (folios 42-49), viii8 (folios 50-57), ix6 (folios 58-63), x6 (folios 64-69), xi8 (folios 70-77), xii8-1 (folios 78-84), xiii10-1 (folios 85-93).</p>
								</collation>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1" ruledLines="12" writtenLines="12">
									<p>Hard-point ruling is visible. </p>
									<p>Hair-side and flesh-side of the folios are distinguishable.
</p>
									<p>Has many illuminations and illustrations, which consist mainly of gold and coloured letters and designs.</p>
									<p>Some parts of the text are written in red ink.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
